# Intelligent Tutoring System

Intelligent Tutoring System is an open-source project exploring how AI can help people learn rather than simply complete tasks.

The project aims to develop an AI-powered learning system based on transparent pedagogical principles, continuous evaluation of learning progress, and collaboration between AI, educators, researchers, developers, and learners.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The project is currently at an early research and development stage. Many fundamental questions about pedagogy, learning assessment, AI decision-making, and system architecture remain open.

## The Problem

Modern AI tools can help people find answers and solve tasks quickly.

However, when AI is used for learning, there is a risk that the cognitive work necessary for learning is transferred from the learner to the AI system. Getting the correct answer or completing a task does not necessarily mean that a person has understood the material, developed new skills, retained knowledge over time, or can apply it in new situations.

We believe that AI in education should be designed not only to improve task performance, but to improve learning itself.

## The Idea

We propose to build an open-source Intelligent Tutoring System in which AI supports and manages the learning process instead of doing the learner's work.

The system should use transparent pedagogical principles, track learning progress, identify difficulties, and adapt the learning strategy to the needs of each learner.

The initial focus of the project is a human-in-the-loop system that supports mathematics tutors working with school students. The system may help educators plan lessons, find learning materials, evaluate student progress, generate questions and exercises, identify learning difficulties, and adapt learning strategies.

In the long term, the project aims to explore how AI systems can take greater responsibility for managing personalized learning while keeping their decisions transparent, explainable, and open to evaluation.

## Vision

We believe that high-quality personalized education should be accessible to anyone who wants to learn.

A person should be able to learn any subject, at any time, at their own pace, and in a learning environment adapted to their needs.

AI can become a powerful partner in this process by helping create personalized learning experiences that adapt to a learner's knowledge, progress, difficulties, and interests.

Our long-term goal is to make learning more accessible, effective, personalized, and engaging while preserving the cognitive effort necessary to develop lasting knowledge and skills.

## Principles

The principles below represent the current direction of the project. They are expected to evolve as we study educational research, work with educators, run experiments, and learn from the community.

### Learning over task completion

The system should optimize for learning, not for completing tasks as quickly as possible.

A correct answer alone does not necessarily mean that learning has occurred.

### Do not do the learner's work

The system should not solve learning tasks for the learner when doing so would remove the cognitive effort necessary for learning.

Instead, it should guide the learner, ask questions, provide appropriate hints, and help them overcome difficulties.

### Preserve productive struggle

Learning requires cognitive effort.

When a learner experiences difficulties, the system should provide enough support to allow progress while preserving meaningful intellectual work.

### Evaluate learning beyond correct answers

Learning progress should not be measured solely through grades or the number of correct answers.

The project aims to explore methods for evaluating understanding, skill development, knowledge retention, and the ability to apply knowledge in new contexts.

### Adapt to the learner

The system should track learning progress, identify difficulties, and adapt the learning strategy.

Learner interests may be used to make learning more engaging, but personalization should not limit the learner's exposure to new ideas or narrow their perspective.

### Verify learning

The system should use questions, exercises, and other forms of assessment to collect evidence that learning has occurred.

The specific methods and criteria for determining whether material has been learned remain an open research question.

### Human in the loop

At the current stage of AI development, the system is intended to support educators rather than replace them.

Educators should be able to review, evaluate, and correct the system's decisions.

### Transparency and explainability

Pedagogical principles, learning strategies, evaluation methods, metrics, experiments, and system decisions should be transparent and open to discussion.

The system should not make important pedagogical decisions that cannot be explained and evaluated.

### Open by default

The project aims to develop its work openly.

This includes source code, pedagogical principles, research, hypotheses, learning models, quality metrics, learning scenarios, architectural decisions, and experiments.

We believe that improving education is too complex a problem to solve alone.

## Current Focus

The first practical use case is supporting a mathematics tutor working with a school student.

For example, while a student is learning quadratic equations, the system could help the tutor:

- plan the learning process;
- find and organize learning materials;
- generate questions and exercises;
- track the student's progress over time;
- identify recurring difficulties;
- suggest changes to the learning strategy;
- adapt exercises to the student's current level;
- evaluate whether the student has understood and retained the material.

This initial use case provides a concrete environment in which the project's pedagogical ideas, system architecture, and learning evaluation methods can be researched and tested.

## Project Status

**Early research and prototyping.**

The project is currently exploring fundamental questions, including:

- Which pedagogical practices should guide the system?
- How should the system respond when a learner is struggling?
- How can learning be evaluated beyond correct answers and grades?
- How should knowledge retention be measured over time?
- How can the transfer of knowledge to new and real-world situations be evaluated?
- Which decisions should be made by AI, educators, and learners?
- How can AI decisions remain transparent and explainable?
- Which metrics should be used to evaluate and improve the quality of the system?

We do not yet have definitive answers to these questions.

The goal of the project is to research them openly, test hypotheses, build prototypes, measure results, and improve the system through collaboration.

## Contributing

The project welcomes contributions from people with different backgrounds.

We are especially interested in collaboration with:

- **Educators** — expertise in teaching and pedagogical practices.
- **Tutors** — practical experience working directly with students.
- **Education researchers** — research, learning methodologies, evaluation methods, and quality benchmarks.
- **AI/ML engineers** — expertise in artificial intelligence and machine learning.
- **Backend developers** — system implementation and infrastructure.
- **System analysts** — requirements analysis, system design, and documentation.
- **UX specialists** — designing a learning system that is simple, accessible, and comfortable to use.
- **Students and parents** — feedback about real learning experiences and needs.

The project is at a very early stage, and the contribution process has not yet been fully defined.

More detailed contribution guidelines will be added as the project develops.

## Inspiration

The project was inspired by the ideas and questions discussed in the [OECD Digital Education Outlook 2026](https://www.oecd.org/en/publications/oecd-digital-education-outlook-2026_062a7394-en.html) about the role of generative AI in education and the difference between improving task performance and improving learning.

